Italian Stocks: Edison, Indesit, Monte Paschi, Popolare, Saras

-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 
2011-02-28T12:06:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-27/intesa-unicredit-edison-fiat-italian-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index  was
little changed, rising less than 0.1 percent to 22,358.92 at
12:52 p.m. in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA (BMPS IM) snapped a
two-day gain, falling 1.5 percent to 96.75 euro cents. Banco
Popolare SC (BP IM) slid 1.5 percent to 2.54 euros.  UniCredit
SpA  (UCG IM), the country’s biggest bank, fell 1.1 percent to
1.85 euros. European Central Bank council member Mario Draghi
urged Italian banks to reinvest profit to strengthen their
finances and expects lenders to raise money to boost capital
before new requirements.    Edison SpA  (EDN IM) surged 3.8 percent to 90.6 euro cents
after gaining 1.5 percent on Feb. 25. Electricite de France SA
may agree with  A2A SpA  (A2A IM) to take full control of Edison
in exchange for power assets, Corriere della Sera reported,
without saying where it got the information.  A2A climbed 2.3 percent to 1.17 euros.  Indesit Co. SpA (IND IM) rose for a second day, adding 4.2
percent to 8.24 euros. The maker of stoves and refrigerators was
upgraded to “buy” at Equita Sim SpA, which added the stock to
its small-caps portfolio.    Saipem SpA  (SPM IM) rose for a second day, adding 1.8
percent to 36.33 euros. The company won a contract that may be
valued at $2.1 billion from Saudi Aramco for offshore works for
the Wasit natural-gas plant development in Saudi Arabia, MEED
reported, without saying where it got the information.    Saras SpA  (SRS IM) soared 4.2 percent to 1.88 euros, the
highest in more than a week. The refiner had its price estimate
lifted at brokerages including Credit Suisse Group AG and CA
Cheuvreux to 1.9 euros from 1.8 euros and to 1.5 euros from 1.25
euros, respectively.    Sogefi SpA  (SO IM) added 1.3 percent to 2.68 euros, a third
consecutive gain. UniCredit Research lifted its price estimate
on the car-parts maker controlled by financier Carlo De Benedetti to 3.1 euros from 2.9 euros. Gruppo Banca Leonardo
increased its price projection to 3.3 euros from 3 euros.    STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM), Europe’s largest chipmaker,
gained 1.2 percent to 9.31 euros, a third straight gain. The
Philadelphia Semiconductor Index rose 2.6 percent on Feb. 25,
the biggest gain in six weeks.    Telecom Italia SpA  (TIT IM) rose 1.1 percent to 1.11 euros
after climbing 5.2 percent on Feb. 25. Goldman Sachs increased
its price estimate on the ordinary shares of Italy’s biggest
phone company to 1.24 euros from 1.22 euros. The brokerage also
increased its price estimate on the savings shares to 1.01 euros
from 1 euro. The savings shares added 2.2 percent to 93.6 euro
cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Francesca Cinelli in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Andrew Rummer at   arummer@bloomberg.net . 